<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<title>UK Day Trips &mdash; July 2026 &middot; Cannock base</title>
<style>
:root{--bg:#0f1216;--card:#1a1f27;--card2:#222834;--ink:#eef2f7;--mut:#9aa7b6;--acc:#5cc8ff;--warm:#ffb454;--line:#2b333f;--good:#8be28b}
*{box-sizing:border-box}
body{margin:0;background:var(--bg);color:var(--ink);font:16px/1.5 -apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,"Segoe UI",Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif}
header{padding:26px 18px 14px;background:linear-gradient(160deg,#1c2530,#0f1216)}
h1{margin:0 0 4px;font-size:22px}
.sub{color:var(--mut);font-size:14px}
.wrap{max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;padding:0 14px 60px}
.note{background:var(--card2);border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:14px;padding:14px 16px;margin:16px 0;font-size:14.5px}
.note b{color:var(--warm)}
.bar{display:flex;justify-content:flex-end;margin:6px 0 0}
#showall{background:var(--card2);color:var(--acc);border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:20px;padding:6px 14px;font-size:13px;font-weight:600;cursor:pointer}
.day{background:var(--card);border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:18px;overflow:hidden;margin:16px 0;box-shadow:0 6px 20px rgba(0,0,0,.25);transition:opacity .2s}
.day img{width:100%;height:210px;object-fit:cover;display:block;background:#222}
.body{padding:14px 16px 18px}
.tag{display:inline-block;font-size:12px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:.3px;color:#0f1216;background:var(--acc);border-radius:20px;padding:3px 10px;margin-bottom:8px}
.tag.rest{background:var(--warm)}
.tag.flex{background:var(--good)}
.dt{font-size:19px;font-weight:700;margin:2px 0 2px}
.drive{color:var(--mut);font-size:13.5px;margin-bottom:10px}
p.desc{margin:8px 0 12px;font-size:15px;color:#dfe6ee}
.links a{display:inline-block;margin:4px 8px 4px 0;font-size:13.5px;color:var(--acc);text-decoration:none;border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:20px;padding:5px 12px}
.links a:active{background:var(--card2)}
a.map{background:#243244;border-color:#2f4256;color:#bfe0ff}
a.ask{background:#2a1f33;border-color:#4b3a5c;color:#e6b8ff}
.cap{font-size:11px;color:#6b7686;padding:0 16px 12px}
details{margin:6px 0 4px;border-top:1px solid var(--line);padding-top:8px}
summary{cursor:pointer;color:var(--acc);font-size:13.5px;font-weight:600;list-style:none;outline:none}
summary::-webkit-details-marker{display:none}
summary::after{content:" \25BE"}
details[open] summary::after{content:" \25B4"}
.det{font-size:14px;color:#dfe6ee}
.det ul{margin:8px 0 4px 18px;padding:0}
.det li{margin:6px 0}
.det b{color:#fff}
footer{color:var(--mut);font-size:12.5px;text-align:center;padding:20px}
.badge{display:inline-block;font-size:10.5px;font-weight:700;color:#0f1216;background:var(--acc);border-radius:6px;padding:1px 6px;margin-left:8px;vertical-align:middle}
.day.today{border-color:var(--acc);box-shadow:0 0 0 2px rgba(92,200,255,.35)}
.day.past{opacity:.5}
.day.past img,.day.past .desc,.day.past .drive,.day.past .links,.day.past details{display:none}
.day.past .body{padding:11px 16px}
.day.past .tag{display:none}
.day.past .dt{font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--mut)}
.day.past .dt::before{content:"\2713  ";color:var(--good);font-weight:700}
body.show-past .day.past{opacity:.85}
body.show-past .day.past img,body.show-past .day.past .desc,body.show-past .day.past .drive,body.show-past .day.past .links,body.show-past .day.past details{display:block}
body.show-past .day.past .tag{display:inline-block}
body.show-past .day.past .dt{font-size:19px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink)}
body.show-past .day.past .dt::before{content:""}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<header>
  <div class="wrap" style="padding-bottom:0">
    <h1>&#128663; UK Day Trips &mdash; July 2026</h1>
    <div class="sub">Based at Cannock, Staffordshire &middot; baby-friendly + historic + scenery &middot; home each night</div>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="wrap">

  <div class="note">
    &#9728;&#65039; <b>Weather &mdash; re-checked 10 Jul (Met Office):</b> high pressure holds &rarr; <b>dry, sunny &amp; warm all week</b>, and the earlier heatwave scare has <b>eased</b> &mdash; a comfortable <b>27&ndash;28&deg;C</b> most days (today Fri 10 is the hottest at ~33&deg;C). The forecast flipped again: last week&rsquo;s &quot;wettest Sunday&quot; is <b>gone &mdash; Sun 12 is now bone dry</b> (&lt;5% rain). A slight afternoon shower / thundery risk creeps in <b>Tue 14&ndash;Thu 16 (30&ndash;40%)</b>, so the rain-resilient days (Chester Zoo, the flex day) sit at the back. Re-check Wales (Mon 13) and the 14&ndash;16 window ~48h out.<br>
    &#128204; <b>Fri 10 is now a pool day + BBQ at your sister&rsquo;s</b> &mdash; the day trips start <b>Sat 11</b>.<br>
    <b>Tip:</b> tap <b>&quot;Where to go &amp; options&quot;</b> on any day for exact spots &amp; baby-friendly ideas, or <b>&quot;Ask for more&quot;</b> to have detail added.
  </div>
  <div class="bar"><button id="showall">Show past days</button></div>
  <div class="day" data-date="2026-07-10">
    
    <div class="body">
      <span class="tag rest">Fri 10 Jul &middot; family day</span>
      <div class="dt">Pool day + BBQ at your sister&rsquo;s</div>
      <div class="drive">&#9201; no driving &middot; hottest day of the week (~33&deg;C)</div>
      <p class="desc">Not a day trip &mdash; a relaxed pool + BBQ day at your sister&rsquo;s, landing right on the week&rsquo;s hottest day. Keep Alfie shaded and topped up with water and sun cream. The day trips kick off tomorrow (Sat 11).</p>
      <details><summary>On the doorstep &mdash; Cannock Chase &amp; around</summary><div class="det">Handy for any spare hour or a soft morning &mdash; all &lt;20 min from your dad&rsquo;s:<ul><li><b>Birches Valley Forest Centre</b> (Rugeley) &mdash; the best all-rounder with a toddler: cafe, flat surfaced buggy trails, the Gruffalo/fairy trail, plus Go Ape &amp; cycle hire for later.</li><li><b>Marquis Drive Visitor Centre</b> (Hednesford) &mdash; cafe, small play area, gentle waymarked walks.</li><li><b>Wild fallow deer</b> &mdash; Cannock Chase has free-roaming herds; best on the open heath around dawn/dusk.</li><li><b>Sherbrook Valley &amp; the Stepping Stones</b> (from Punch Bowl car park) &mdash; prettiest short walk; a carrier beats the pram on the rougher stretches.</li><li><b>German Military Cemetery &amp; Katyn Memorial</b> &mdash; quiet and moving, ~15 min away.</li><li><b>Shoal Hill Common</b> &mdash; quick local viewpoint stroll.</li></ul></div></details>
      <div class="links"><a class="ask" href="https://zlviiufrnx354pyk6bc9vy9dauofbwvq.ui.nabu.casa/trip-ask?a=Cannock%20Chase">Ask for more &#8599;</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="day" data-date="2026-07-11">
    <img loading="lazy" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Shugborough Estate + Lichfield"><div class="cap">Shugborough Hall &middot; Wikimedia Commons</div>
    <div class="body">
      <span class="tag">Sat 11 Jul &middot; sunny, 28&deg;</span>
      <div class="dt">Shugborough Estate + Lichfield</div>
      <div class="drive">&#9201; ~15&ndash;20 min each way</div>
      <p class="desc">Gentle opener for the trips. Morning at the National Trust estate &mdash; walled garden, riverside parkland, farm animals, all pram-friendly. Then Lichfield&rsquo;s three-spired medieval cathedral and Beacon Park playground. Shortest drive on the list, so easiest to cut short if Alfie&rsquo;s tired after the BBQ day.</p>
      <details><summary>Where to go &amp; options</summary><div class="det"><ul><li><b>Shugborough (NT):</b> the model farm (animals, old dairy), walled kitchen garden, and easy parkland walks by the River Sow. Free for NT members; mostly buggy-friendly with some gravel. Tearoom on site.</li><li><b>Lichfield:</b> the only English cathedral with three spires (step-free access); <b>Beacon Park</b> has a big playground, boating and a summer splash pad; Erasmus Darwin House if you fancy history.</li><li><b>With Alfie:</b> pram fine across most of both; combine as a half-day each or lean into whichever he&rsquo;s happiest at.</li></ul></div></details>
      <div class="links"><a href="https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/visit/staffordshire/shugborough-estate">Shugborough (NT) &#8599;</a><a href="https://www.lichfield-cathedral.org/">Lichfield Cathedral &#8599;</a><a class="map" href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cannock/Shugborough+Estate">Directions &#8599;</a><a class="ask" href="https://zlviiufrnx354pyk6bc9vy9dauofbwvq.ui.nabu.casa/trip-ask?a=Shugborough%20%2B%20Lichfield">Ask for more &#8599;</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="day" data-date="2026-07-12">
    <img loading="lazy" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Ironbridge Gorge + Blists Hill"><div class="cap">Blists Hill Victorian Town, Ironbridge &middot; Wikimedia Commons</div>
    <div class="body">
      <span class="tag">Sun 12 Jul &middot; sunny &amp; dry, 27&deg;</span>
      <div class="dt">Ironbridge Gorge + Blists Hill</div>
      <div class="drive">&#9201; ~35 min each way &middot; ~55 mi round</div>
      <p class="desc">The forecast flipped &mdash; Sun 12 is now bone dry &amp; sunny (&lt;5% rain), so the open-air Blists Hill goes ahead as planned. UNESCO World Heritage: a full recreated Victorian town with costumed characters and working shops; wide flat lanes make it one of the most pram-friendly attractions anywhere. Then the Iron Bridge itself and a riverside lunch.</p>
      <details><summary>Where to go &amp; options</summary><div class="det"><ul><li><b>Blists Hill:</b> allow 2&ndash;3h. Change real money for old coins at the bank, watch the foundry/candle-makers, and get fish &amp; chips fried in beef dripping. Flat, wide, very buggy-friendly. Parking on site.</li><li><b>The Iron Bridge &amp; town:</b> stroll the world&rsquo;s first iron bridge and the riverside; cafes in Ironbridge village.</li><li><b>Wet-weather backup:</b> <b>Enginuity</b> is a fully indoor hands-on museum next door &mdash; good if a shower sneaks in. A &quot;passport&quot; ticket covers all 10 Gorge museums if you want more.</li></ul></div></details>
      <div class="links"><a href="https://www.ironbridge.org.uk/visit/attractions/blists-hill-victorian-town/">Blists Hill &#8599;</a><a href="https://www.ironbridge.org.uk/">Ironbridge Gorge &#8599;</a><a class="map" href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cannock/Blists+Hill+Victorian+Town">Directions &#8599;</a><a class="ask" href="https://zlviiufrnx354pyk6bc9vy9dauofbwvq.ui.nabu.casa/trip-ask?a=Ironbridge%20%2B%20Blists%20Hill">Ask for more &#8599;</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="day" data-date="2026-07-13">
    <img loading="lazy" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="North Wales &mdash; Conwy + Llandudno"><div class="cap">Conwy Castle &middot; Wikimedia Commons</div>
    <div class="body">
      <span class="tag">Mon 13 Jul &middot; sunny, 25&deg;, breezy</span>
      <div class="dt">North Wales &mdash; Conwy + Llandudno</div>
      <div class="drive">&#9201; ~1 hr 45 each way (the big one)</div>
      <p class="desc">A proper adventure day, saved for a quiet weekday. Forecast is ideal &mdash; sunny, ~25&deg;C with a fresh sea breeze (gusts ~27mph, so a windproof layer on the prom). Conwy is a spectacular walled town with one of Europe&rsquo;s best-preserved castles on the estuary; then 10 min to Llandudno&rsquo;s grand Victorian seaside prom (flat, pram-perfect) and the Great Orme tram. Set off early.</p>
      <details><summary>Where to go &amp; options</summary><div class="det"><ul><li><b>Conwy:</b> the castle has steep spiral steps (carrier, not pram, inside); the walkable town walls, the quay, and the <b>Smallest House in Britain</b> are all easy. Good chippy/cafes on the quay.</li><li><b>Llandudno:</b> the flat Victorian promenade and pier are pram-perfect; ride the <b>Great Orme Tramway</b> or cable car for big views; sandy-ish beach for a paddle.</li><li><b>If you want gardens:</b> <b>Bodnant Garden</b> (NT) is ~20 min inland &mdash; buggy-friendly terraces.</li><li><b>Logistics:</b> longest drive of the week (~210 mi round). Leave ~9am, pack wind layers and snacks.</li></ul></div></details>
      <div class="links"><a href="https://cadw.gov.wales/visit/places-to-visit/conwy-castle">Conwy Castle &#8599;</a><a href="https://www.visitllandudno.org.uk/">Visit Llandudno &#8599;</a><a class="map" href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cannock/Conwy+Castle">Directions &#8599;</a><a class="ask" href="https://zlviiufrnx354pyk6bc9vy9dauofbwvq.ui.nabu.casa/trip-ask?a=Conwy%20%2B%20Llandudno%20(North%20Wales)">Ask for more &#8599;</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="day" data-date="2026-07-14">
    <img loading="lazy" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Chatsworth House + Bakewell"><div class="cap">Chatsworth House, Peak District &middot; Wikimedia Commons</div>
    <div class="body">
      <span class="tag">Tue 14 Jul &middot; warm 28&deg;, PM cloud</span>
      <div class="dt">Chatsworth House + Bakewell</div>
      <div class="drive">&#9201; ~1 hr each way</div>
      <p class="desc">The showstopper. One of England&rsquo;s grandest stately homes in glorious parkland. Do the farmyard, adventure playground and river walk (all pram-friendly) rather than the full house if Alfie&rsquo;s restless. Then 15 min to Bakewell for the classic Peak market town and a warm Bakewell pudding. A slight chance of afternoon showers (~30%) &mdash; the house is the perfect rain-resilient fallback.</p>
      <details><summary>Where to go &amp; options</summary><div class="det"><ul><li><b>Chatsworth farmyard &amp; adventure playground:</b> the toddler magnet &mdash; animals, a big timber playground and woodland walk; the garden&rsquo;s cascade and fountains are made for a splash. Go early, it gets busy; pre-book online.</li><li><b>The house:</b> worth it if Alfie naps in a carrier &mdash; grand painted halls and sculpture gallery.</li><li><b>Bakewell:</b> riverside and ducks, the original Bakewell pudding shops, and a pretty market town for a wander (market day Monday).</li></ul></div></details>
      <div class="links"><a href="https://www.chatsworth.org/">Chatsworth &#8599;</a><a href="https://www.visitpeakdistrict.com/explore/bakewell">Bakewell &#8599;</a><a class="map" href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cannock/Chatsworth+House">Directions &#8599;</a><a class="ask" href="https://zlviiufrnx354pyk6bc9vy9dauofbwvq.ui.nabu.casa/trip-ask?a=Chatsworth%20%2B%20Bakewell">Ask for more &#8599;</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="day" data-date="2026-07-15">
    <img loading="lazy" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Chester Zoo or Shrewsbury"><div class="cap">Chester Zoo &middot; Wikimedia Commons</div>
    <div class="body">
      <span class="tag">Wed 15 Jul &middot; warm 28&deg;, PM showers</span>
      <div class="dt">Chester Zoo <span style="color:var(--mut);font-weight:400">or</span> Shrewsbury</div>
      <div class="drive">&#9201; Zoo ~1 hr &middot; Shrewsbury ~45 min</div>
      <p class="desc">Pick your energy level. Chester Zoo is world-class, totally pram-built and an easy full day &mdash; and its big indoor houses make it the right call if the ~30% afternoon showers arrive. Or keep it relaxed with Shrewsbury &mdash; the prettiest medieval town nearby, Tudor streets in a loop of the Severn, plus the big pram-friendly Quarry Park.</p>
      <details><summary>Where to go &amp; options</summary><div class="det"><ul><li><b>Chester Zoo:</b> aim for <b>The Islands</b>, the indoor <b>Monsoon Forest</b> (warm, dry &mdash; your rain backup), the butterfly house and the playground; the land train saves little legs. A full day; pre-book.</li><li><b>Shrewsbury alt:</b> <b>Quarry Park</b> &amp; the Dingle gardens are pram-perfect by the river; add the castle and Tudor lanes.</li><li><b>Chester city alt:</b> the Roman walls, the two-tier medieval <b>Rows</b>, and a short river cruise.</li></ul></div></details>
      <div class="links"><a href="https://www.chesterzoo.org/">Chester Zoo &#8599;</a><a href="https://www.originalshrewsbury.co.uk/">Visit Shrewsbury &#8599;</a><a class="map" href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cannock/Chester+Zoo">Zoo directions &#8599;</a><a class="map" href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cannock/Shrewsbury">Shrewsbury &#8599;</a><a class="ask" href="https://zlviiufrnx354pyk6bc9vy9dauofbwvq.ui.nabu.casa/trip-ask?a=Chester%20Zoo%20%2F%20Shrewsbury">Ask for more &#8599;</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="day" data-date="2026-07-16">
    <img loading="lazy" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Cotswolds &mdash; Bourton-on-the-Water or rest"><div class="cap">Bourton-on-the-Water, Cotswolds &middot; Wikimedia Commons</div>
    <div class="body">
      <span class="tag flex">Thu 16 Jul &middot; flex &middot; showers/thundery risk</span>
      <div class="dt">Cotswolds &mdash; Bourton-on-the-Water <span style="color:var(--mut);font-weight:400">or</span> rest</div>
      <div class="drive">&#9201; ~1 hr 15 each way</div>
      <p class="desc">Optional last outing, or slack and packing before the London leg. Highest shower/thundery risk of the week (~40%), so play it by the morning. If it&rsquo;s clear, Bourton-on-the-Water is chocolate-box England &mdash; the little River Windrush runs through the green under low stone bridges, paddling-friendly and flat (arrive ~10:30 for parking).</p>
      <details><summary>Where to go &amp; options</summary><div class="det"><ul><li><b>Bourton-on-the-Water:</b> paddle in the shallow Windrush under the low bridges; <b>Birdland</b>, the <b>Model Village</b>, and the Motoring Museum are all easy with a toddler (and indoor-ish if it drizzles).</li><li><b>Stow-on-the-Wold</b> (10 min): handsome market square and the famous yew-flanked church door.</li><li><b>Prettiest lanes:</b> Lower Slaughter or Bibury if you want a classic Cotswold stroll.</li><li><b>Wet plan B:</b> stay local &mdash; Birmingham <b>Thinktank</b> science museum on the way, or just pack for London.</li></ul></div></details>
      <div class="links"><a href="https://www.bourtoninfo.com/">Bourton-on-the-Water &#8599;</a><a class="map" href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cannock/Bourton-on-the-Water">Directions &#8599;</a><a class="ask" href="https://zlviiufrnx354pyk6bc9vy9dauofbwvq.ui.nabu.casa/trip-ask?a=Cotswolds%20(Bourton)">Ask for more &#8599;</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="note" style="margin-top:22px">
    <b>Swaps if you&rsquo;d rather:</b> Warwick Castle (~50 min), Stratford-upon-Avon (~50 min), Bridgnorth + Severn Valley steam railway (~40 min), or Snowdonia proper on the North Wales day.
  </div>

  <footer>
    Fri 17 Jul &rarr; London leg &middot; fly home SQ313 Sun 19 Jul.<br>
    <b>Mileage:</b> the whole week &asymp; <b>790&ndash;810 mi</b> vs your <b>1,050-mi</b> rental allowance &rarr; ~240 mi to spare. The Wales day (~210 mi) is the single biggest chunk.<br>
    Drive times one-way from Cannock, approximate. Photos: Wikimedia Commons. Built by Claude Code 5 Jul; rebuilt interactive + daily-reviewed 10 Jul 2026. Past days auto-collapse.
  </footer>
</div>
<script>
(function(){
  var t=new Date(); t.setHours(0,0,0,0);
  var days=document.querySelectorAll('.day[data-date]'), past=0;
  days.forEach(function(d){
    var p=d.getAttribute('data-date').split('-');
    var dd=new Date(+p[0],+p[1]-1,+p[2]);
    if(dd<t){ d.classList.add('past'); past++; }
    else if(dd.getTime()===t.getTime()){ d.classList.add('today');
      var b=document.createElement('span'); b.className='badge'; b.textContent='TODAY';
      var dt=d.querySelector('.dt'); if(dt){ dt.appendChild(b); } }
  });
  var btn=document.getElementById('showall');
  if(btn){
    if(past===0){ btn.style.display='none'; }
    else { var lbl='past day'+(past>1?'s':'');
      btn.textContent='Show '+past+' '+lbl;
      btn.addEventListener('click',function(){
        var on=document.body.classList.toggle('show-past');
        btn.textContent=(on?'Hide':'Show '+past)+' '+lbl;
      });
    }
  }
})();
</script>
</body>
</html>